msgid ""
"The major problem with the ``people`` table is that there is a single "
"address field which contains a person's entire address. Thinking about our "
"theoretical ``address`` table earlier in this lesson, we know that an "
"address is made up of many different properties. By storing all these "
"properties in one field, we make it much harder to update and query our "
"data. We therefore need to split the address field into the various "
"properties. This would give us a table which has the following structure::"
msgstr ""
"Glavni problem sa tabelom ``people`` jeste to što postoji jedno polje adrese"
" koje sadrži celu adresu osobe. Razmišljajući o našoj teorijskoj tabeli "
"``address`` ranije u ovoj lekciji, znamo da se adresa sastoji od mnogo "
"različitih svojstava. Čuvanjem svih tih svojstava u jednom polju mnogo "
"otežavamo ažuriranje i postavljanje upita nad našim podacima. Zbog toga "
"polje adrese moramo podeliti na različita svojstva. To bi nam dalo tabelu "
"sledeće strukture::"

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:233
msgid ""
"In the next section, you will learn about Foreign Key relationships which "
"could be used in this example to further improve our database's structure."
msgstr ""
"U sledećem odeljku učićete o vezama stranih ključeva, koje bi se u ovom "
"primeru mogle iskoristiti za dalje poboljšanje strukture naše baze podataka."

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:237
msgid "Indexes"
msgstr "Indeksi"

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:239
msgid ""
"A database index is a data structure that improves the speed of data "
"retrieval operations on a database table. *- Wikipedia*"
msgstr ""
"Indeks baze podataka je struktura podataka koja povećava brzinu preuzimanja "
"podataka iz tabele baze podataka. *- Vikipedija*"

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:242
msgid ""
"Imagine you are reading a textbook and looking for the explanation of a "
"concept - and the textbook has no index! You will have to start reading at "
"one cover and work your way through the entire book until you find the "
"information you need. The index at the back of a book helps you to jump "
"quickly to the page with the relevant information:"
msgstr ""
"Zamislite da čitate udžbenik i tražite objašnjenje nekog pojma - a udžbenik "
"nema indeks! Moraćete da počnete od korica i pređete celu knjigu dok ne "
"nađete informaciju koja vam treba. Indeks na kraju knjige pomaže vam da brzo"
" skočite na stranicu sa odgovarajućom informacijom:"

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:252
msgid "Now searches on name will be faster:"
msgstr "Sada će pretrage po nazivu biti brže:"

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:271
msgid "Sequences"
msgstr "Sekvence"

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:273
msgid ""
"A sequence is a unique number generator. It is normally used to create a "
"unique identifier for a column in a table."
msgstr ""
"Sekvenca je generator jedinstvenih brojeva. Obično se koristi za pravljenje "
"jedinstvenog identifikatora za kolonu u tabeli."

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:276
msgid ""
"In this example, id is a sequence - the number is incremented each time a "
"record is added to the table:"
msgstr ""
"U ovom primeru, id je sekvenca - broj se uvećava svaki put kada se u tabelu "
"doda zapis:"

#: ../../docs/training_manual/database_concepts/db_intro.rst:287
msgid "Entity Relationship Diagramming"
msgstr "Dijagram entiteta i veza"

